          "body": "Psalm 33:16-17 performs a specific polemical function: it names the three pillars of ancient Near Eastern security and declares all three inadequate. The king's army (numerical superiority), the warrior's personal strength, and the horse (cavalry — the tank of the ancient world) — all three represent categories of power that every surrounding culture regarded as sufficient for deliverance. Israel was perpetually tempted to trust these same instruments, which is why the prophets repeatedly thundered against alliance with Egypt's horses (Isaiah 31:1-3) and why Deuteronomy 17:16 prohibited the king from multiplying horses. The Psalm's polemic is not anti-military pacifism; it is anti-idolatry theology. The problem is not the army or the horse but the *hope* placed in them — the word in 33:17 is sheqer, literally 'a lie, a deception.' Any instrument of power treated as the ultimate source of deliverance is, by that treatment, a lie. The demolition of the alternatives is what gives 33:18's 'Behold' its rhetorical force: if the greatest military powers cannot deliver, and the eye of the Lord is on you, then His eye is not merely a comfort — it is your only sufficient protection."
